nt|
Suppose you are South and the bidding has gone:
|ht|d|cs|1|at|^-{|ia| 1hp1sp2cp?|at|}
^-


|cs|3|ht|h|at|^m@3|at|
^-You hold:

{|ih|psq9842h53dk872c94|at|}
^-|
lb|*BWhat call would you make?^^2H|

cs|2|ht|h|at| @1^m@2|at|
^-Change your hand to:

{|ih|psat43hktd6532cqt9|at|}
^-|
lb|*BWhat call would you make now?^^2H|

nt||ht|b|cs|1|at|^-{|ia| 1hp1sp2cp!2h|at|}


|cs|4|at|{ That's right - 2@H is the correct call with both of these hands! }
^-|
cs|3|ht|i|at| @0@1^m@3|at|^-
{|ih|psq9842h53dk872c94|at|}
^-|
cs|2|ht|i|at| @1^m@2|at|^-
{|ih|psat43hktd6532cqt9|at|}
^-
@0@1
The 2@H rebid has a very wide range. The first hand is a minimum in terms of point count and it is possible that none of its high cards will be working. The second hand is a maximum in terms of high cards, all of which rate to be working (there are some nice intermediate cards in this hand as well). The wide range of responder's 2@H rebid will often give opener a very difficult guess as to whether or not he should move towards game.|
